**
** IM7/8552, 190 g/m^2, 35% resin content
** Hand layup, cured per NCAMP Process Specification NPS 81228
** Units: N, mm, s
** Nominal ply thickness: 0.183 mm
** Nominal density: 1.57e-9 ton/mm^3
**
** References
** 1. P. P. Camanho, P. Maimí, C. G. Dávila. Prediction of size effects in notched
**    laminates using continuum damage mechanics. Compos Sci Technol 2007;
**    67:2715–27.
** 3. S. Wanthal, J. D. Schaefer, B. Justusson, I. Hyder, S. Engelstad, and C.
**    Rose, "Verification and Validation Process for Progressive Damage and
**    Failure Analysis Methods in the NASA Advanced Composites Consortium,"
**    presented at the American Society for Composites 32nd Technical
**    Conference, West Lafayette, IN, Oct. 2017.
** 5. G. Catalanotti, J. Xavier, and P. P. Camanho, Measurement of the
**    compressive crack resistance curve of composites using the size effect
**    law, Composites Part A: Applied Science and Manufacturing, vol. 56, pp.
**    300–307, 2014, doi: 10.1016/j.compositesa.2013.10.017.
** 8. G. Catalanotti, A. Arteiro, M. Hayati, and P. P. Camanho, Determination
**    of the mode I crack resistance curve of polymer composites using the
**    size-effect law, Engineering Fracture Mechanics, vol. 118, pp. 49–65,
**    Mar. 2014, doi: 10.1016/j.engfracmech.2013.10.021.
** 9. E. Clarkson, "Hexcel 8552 IM7 Unidirectional Prepreg 190 gsm & 35% RC
**    Qualification Statistical Analysis," NCP-RP-2009-028, Jun. 2011.
** 10.NASA Internal Test Report, values published in Ref. 3.
** 12.G. B. Murri, "Evaluation of Delamination Onset and Growth
**    Characterization Methods under Mode I Fatigue Loading," NASA/TM-2013-
**    217966, Feb. 2013.
** 13.J. G. Ratcliffe and W. M. Johnston, "Influence of Mixed Mode I-Mode II
**    Loading on Fatigue Delamination Growth Characteristics of a Graphite
**    Epoxy Tape Laminate," presented at the American Society for Composites
**    29th Technical Conference, La Jolla, CA, Sep. 2014.
** 14.C. A. Rose, C. G. Dávila, and F. A. Leone, "Analysis methods for
**    progressive damage of composite structures," Hampton, VA, NASA/TM–2013-
**    218024, Jul. 2013.
** 16.A. S. Kaddour and M. J. Hinton, "Input data for test cases used in
**    benchmarking triaxial failure theories of composites," Journal of
**    Composite Materials, vol. 46, no. 19–20, Art. no. 19–20, Sep. 2012,
**    doi: 10.1177/0021998312449886.
**
** Notes
** a. E1C = 140653.  Ref 9.
**    Use E1T for materials in tension and E1C for materials in
**    compression. (E1T+E1C)/2 can be used for materials in bending.
** b. E2T = E2C (tensile and compressive moduli are equal)
** c. Poisson's ratios are assumed values, not based on test data.
** d. alpha0 is loosely based on test observations, Ref. 1 (134 gsm).
** d. Transverse isotropy is assumed
** e. Assumed equal to values for 134 gsm material, Ref. 1
** f. Assumed equal to values for 134 gsm material, Ref. 14 and 16
** g. From Ref 3., note this is an assumed value.
** h. Assumed equal to values for 134 gsm material, Ref. 8
** i. Assumed equal to values for 134 gsm material, Ref. 5
** j. Longitudinal elastic nonlinearity (fiber nonlinearity) has not been
**    measured. Typically this property is omitted (fiber nonlinearity is
**    ignored). The value cl = 11 was obtained by fitting to test data for
**    AS4/8552 in this reference:
**    M. Harráez, A. C. Bergan, C. González, and C. S. Lopes, "Modeling Fiber
**    Kinking at the Microscale and Mesoscale," Hampton, VA, NASA/TP-2018-
**    220105, Oct. 2018. Accessed: Feb. 21, 2019.
** k. The width of the kinkband w_kb is only required for FKT. See
**    `IM7-8552-C3D-25sv.inp` for examples where it is used.
** l. T_sf is only required for estimating thermal strain when a nonzero
**    reference temperature is desired.
** m. mu = {0, 0.3}, both are assumed values
